  "instructions_json": {
    "time_total_min": 90,
    "steps": [
      {
        "step_no": 1,
        "text": "Preheat the oven to 400°F (205°C). Halve the spaghetti squash lengthwise and scoop out seeds. Brush the cut sides with half of the oil and sprinkle with a portion of the salt and pepper. Place cut-side down on a rimmed baking sheet and roast until fork-tender and strands separate easily.",
        "time_min": 40
      },
      {
        "step_no": 2,
        "text": "While squash roasts, heat a large heavy-bottomed skillet or Dutch oven over medium heat. Add the chopped bacon and render until fat is crisp and translucent. Transfer crispy bacon to a paper towel, reserving rendered fat in the pan.",
        "time_min": 8
      },
      {
        "step_no": 3,
        "text": "Increase heat to medium-high, add the remaining oil if needed, then add the ground beef. Break meat into small pieces and brown thoroughly until no pink remains, allowing fond to form on the pan.",
        "time_min": 6
      },
      {
        "step_no": 4,
        "text": "Push meat to one side of the pan, add diced onion, carrot, and celery to the cleared space and sauté until softened and translucent. Stir vegetables into the browned meat.",
        "time_min": 6
      },
      {
        "step_no": 5,
        "text": "Add minced garlic and tomato paste to the pan and cook, stirring, until the paste darkens slightly and garlic is fragrant to deepen flavor.",
        "time_min": 2
      },
      {
        "step_no": 6,
        "text": "If using, deglaze the pan with red wine, scraping up browned bits; allow alcohol to reduce by about half. Then add crushed tomatoes, beef stock, bay leaf, dried oregano, dried thyme, red pepper flakes if using, and the reserved cooked bacon. Stir to combine and bring to a simmer.",
        "time_min": 4
      },
      {
        "step_no": 7,
        "text": "Reduce heat to low and simmer gently, partially covered, until the sauce thickens and flavors meld. Taste and adjust seasoning with remaining salt and pepper as it reduces.",
        "time_min": 20
      },
      {
        "step_no": 8,
        "text": "When squash is cool enough to handle, use a fork to rake out spaghetti-like strands into a serving dish or back in the squash shells. Toss strands with a small splash of olive oil and season lightly with salt and pepper.",
        "time_min": 4
      },
      {
        "step_no": 9,
        "text": "Ladle the Bolognese sauce over the spaghetti squash strands, finish with chopped basil and parsley and a squeeze of lemon juice if desired. Serve hot.",
        "time_min": 0
      }
    ]
  },
